Data Loading¶






















The dataset DF contains the following columns:


    

  • 'name': Name of the Song
    • 

  • 'year': Year of Release
    • 

  • 'artists': All the artists in the song
    • 

  • 'id': Unique id for each song
    • 

  • 'popularity': how popular was the song (range 0 to 100)
    • 

  • 'valence': range from 0 to 1
    • 

  • 'acousticness': range from 0 to 1
    • 

  • 'danceability': range from 0 to 1
    • 

  • 'duration_ms': duration of song in ms
    • 

  • 'energy': range from 0 to 1
    • 

  • 'explicit': 0-not explicit and 1-explict
    • 

  • 'instrumentalness': range from 0 to 1
    • 

  • 'key':All keys on octave encoded as values from 0 to 11, C as 0, C# as 1 and so on
    • 

  • 'liveness': range from 0 to 1
    • 

  • 'loudness': ranging from -60 to 0
    • 

  • 'mode': 0-Minor and 1-major
    • 

  • 'speechiness': range from 0 to 1
    • 

  • 'tempo': ranging from 50 to 150
    •

zerotoone = yearby[['acousticness', 'danceability',
                    'energy', 'instrumentalness',
                    'liveness', 'valence','year']]
df = zerotoone.copy()
dfn = df[df.year > 1945]

Key Insights:¶


    

  • Acousticness of songs decreased with time, there was a very sharp drop 1965 to 1975
    • 

  • Dancebility of songs increased with time
    • 

  • there was a rapid increase in the Energy of the songs in th3 60's
    • 

  • Instrumentalness decreased with the increase in time
    • 

  • Liveness and Valence have remained quite stable throughout the time
    •

Kmeans Clustering¶






















K-Means clustering is an unsupervised learning algorithm, which is used when you have unlabeled data. The aim of this algorithm is to find groups in the data. K-means clustering algorithm has many uses for grouping text documents, images, videos, and much more. It works iteratively to assign each data point to one of the groups based on the Euclidean distance.

BIRCH Clustering¶






















It is a memory-efficient, online-learning algorithm provided. It constructs a tree data structure with the cluster centroids being read off the leaf. These can be either the final cluster centroids or can be provided as input to another clustering algorithm such as AgglomerativeClustering.

Mini-Batch Kmeans Clustering¶






















Mini Batch K-means algorithm‘s main idea is to use small random batches of data of a fixed size, so they can be stored in memory. Each iteration a new random sample from the dataset is obtained and used to update the clusters and this is repeated until convergence.


















In [25]:






from sklearn.cluster import MiniBatchKMeans





















In [26]:

Fuzzy C Mean Clustering¶






















Fuzzy C mean works by assigning membership to each data point corresponding to each cluster center on the basis of distance between the cluster center and the data point. More the data is near to the cluster center more is its membership towards the particular cluster center.

Gausian Mixture Model¶






















Gaussian Mixture Model or Mixture of Gaussian as it is sometimes called, is not so much a model as it is a probability distribution. It is a universally used model for generative unsupervised learning or clustering. It is also called Expectation-Maximization Clustering or EM Clustering and is based on the optimization strategy.

Accuracy for these clustering algorithms¶






















We will be using the Calinski Harabasz score from sklearn.metrics


Calinski-Harabasz (CH) Index (introduced by Calinski and Harabasz in 1974) can be used to evaluate the model when ground truth labels are not known where the validation of how well the clustering has been done is made using quantities and features inherent to the dataset. The CH Index (also known as Variance ratio criterion) is a measure of how similar an object is to its own cluster (cohesion) compared to other clusters (separation).


The Higher the score the Better the Result.

The role of K-Means clustering in this recommendation system is to group songs with similar feature vectors into clusters. When a user provides a list of input songs, the system calculates the center of these input songs and then looks for songs in the same cluster or near the center in the feature space as recommendations. This approach is based on the assumption that songs within the same cluster or close to the center are more likely to be similar in terms of their features, and therefore, users might be interested in them as recommendations.

def input_preprocessor(song_list, dataset):
   
    song_vectors = []
    
    for song in song_list:
        try:
            song_data = dataset[(dataset['name'] == song['name']) & 
                                (dataset['year'] == song['year'])].iloc[0]
       
        except IndexError:
            song_data = None
            
        if song_data is None:
            print('Warning: {} does not exist in our database'.format(song['name']))
            continue
            
        song_vectors.append(song_data[features].values)  

    return np.mean(np.array(list(song_vectors)), axis=0)

def tracks_groupby(list_of_dict):
    
    tracks_dict = {}
    for key in list_of_dict[0].keys():
        tracks_dict[key] = []
    
    for dictionary in list_of_dict:
        for key, value in dictionary.items():
            tracks_dict[key].append(value)
                  
    return tracks_dict

def Music_Recommender(song_list, dataset, n_songs=10):

    groupby_input_tracks = tracks_groupby(song_list)
    song_center = input_preprocessor(song_list, dataset)
    
    
    scaler = song_cluster_pipeline.steps[0][1]
    scaled_data = scaler.transform(dataset[features])
    scaled_song_center = scaler.transform(song_center.reshape(1, -1))
    
    
    ed_dist = euclidean_distances(scaled_song_center, scaled_data)

    
    index = list(np.argsort(ed_dist)[:,:n_songs][0])
    rec_output = dataset.iloc[index]
  
    
    return rec_output[metadata_cols]
